Dataset Overview¶

The dataset used in this study contains 768 simulated residential buildings generated using the Ecotect software.
Each building varies in architectural and thermal characteristics such as compactness, surface area, glazing percentage, and orientation.
The goal is to predict two continuous variables:

  • Heating Load (HL)
  • Cooling Load (CL)

These values represent the energy demand required to maintain thermal comfort inside the building.

Below is a preview of the first 15 samples of the dataset.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

To better understand the relationships between architectural features and energy performance, we begin by exploring the distribution of the variables and their correlations.
This helps identify which features have the strongest influence on heating and cooling loads.

1. Correlation Heatmap¶

In [6]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")

plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
plt.title("Correlation Matrix of Building Features")
plt.show()

Correlation Analysis¶

The correlation matrix below reveals key relationships between architectural features and energy demand.

  • Relative Compactness shows a strong positive correlation with both Heating Load (0.62) and Cooling Load (0.63), indicating that more compact buildings tend to be more energy-efficient.
  • Surface Area and Roof Area are negatively correlated with energy loads, suggesting that larger external surfaces increase thermal losses.
  • Overall Height has the strongest positive correlation with both Heating Load (0.89) and Cooling Load (0.90), meaning taller buildings require more energy to maintain thermal comfort.
  • Glazing Area has a moderate positive correlation with Heating Load (0.27), which aligns with the idea that more windows can increase heat loss.
  • Orientation and Glazing Area Distribution show very weak correlations, implying minimal impact on energy demand in this simulation setup.
  • Heating Load and Cooling Load are highly correlated (0.98), which suggests that buildings requiring more heating also tend to require more cooling.

These insights help identify which features are most influential and should be prioritized in predictive modeling.

2. Distribution of Heating and Cooling Loads¶

In [7]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(12,5))
sns.histplot(df["Heating_Load"], kde=True, ax=ax[0], color="firebrick")
sns.histplot(df["Cooling_Load"], kde=True, ax=ax[1], color="steelblue")

ax[0].set_title("Heating Load Distribution")
ax[1].set_title("Cooling Load Distribution")

plt.show()

Distribution of Heating and Cooling Loads¶

The histograms above illustrate the distribution of the two target variables: Heating Load (HL) and Cooling Load (CL).
Both distributions show a clear bimodal pattern, indicating that the dataset contains two dominant groups of buildings with different thermal behaviors.

Key observations¶

  • Heating Load displays two peaks:

    • One around ~13 units
    • Another around ~30 units
      This suggests that some building configurations are significantly more energy-efficient than others.

  • Cooling Load also exhibits two peaks:

    • A major peak near ~15 units
    • A secondary peak around ~32 units
      This mirrors the heating pattern, which aligns with the strong correlation (0.98) between HL and CL.

  • The presence of two clusters implies that the dataset may represent two distinct building archetypes, possibly driven by differences in:

    • compactness
    • height
    • glazing percentage
    • roof area

Understanding these distributions is essential before training a predictive model, as it helps identify potential non-linearities and the need for models capable of capturing complex relationships.

3. Relationship Between Compactness and Energy Demand¶

In [8]:
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="Relative_Compactness", y="Heating_Load", color="darkgreen")
plt.title("Relative Compactness vs Heating Load")
plt.show()

Relationship Between Relative Compactness and Heating Load¶

The scatter plot above illustrates how Relative Compactness influences the Heating Load of the simulated buildings.

Key insights¶

  • There is a clear upward trend: buildings with higher compactness tend to require more heating energy.
  • This may seem counterintuitive at first, since compact buildings usually lose less heat.
    However, in this dataset, compactness is strongly linked to Overall Height, which has a major impact on energy demand.
  • The plot reveals two distinct clusters, consistent with the bimodal distribution observed earlier.
    These clusters likely correspond to:
    • low-height buildings (3.5 m)
    • high-height buildings (7.0 m)
  • The variability within each cluster suggests that other featuressuch as glazing area or roof areaalso influence heating performance.

This visualization reinforces the idea that heating demand is driven by a combination of geometric factors, not a single variable. It also highlights the need for a predictive model capable of capturing non-linear relationships.

4. Effect of Glazing Area on Heating Load¶

In [9]:
sns.boxplot(data=df, x="Glazing_Area", y="Heating_Load", palette="viridis")
plt.title("Glazing Area vs Heating Load")
plt.show()

Effect of Glazing Area on Heating Load¶

The box plot above illustrates how different glazing area percentages affect the Heating Load of the simulated buildings.

Key insights¶

  • Buildings with 0% glazing tend to have the lowest heating loads, as expected, since windows are typically the weakest part of the thermal envelope.
  • As the glazing area increases from 0.0 0.1 0.25 0.4, the median heating load generally rises.
    This indicates that larger window areas lead to greater heat losses during colder periods.
  • The spread of the distributions also increases with higher glazing percentages, suggesting that glazing interacts with other features (orientation, height, compactness) to produce more variability in heating performance.
  • The effect is not perfectly linear: the jump from 0.25 to 0.4 glazing area shows a noticeable increase in heating load, reinforcing the idea that excessive glazing can significantly reduce energy efficiency.

This visualization highlights the importance of carefully balancing natural lighting benefits with thermal performance when designing building faades.

Heating Load vs Overall Height¶

In [10]:
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="Overall_Height",
    y="Heating_Load",
    color="darkred"
)

plt.title("Overall Height vs Heating Load")
plt.show()

Relationship Between Overall Height and Heating Load¶

The scatter plot above reveals a very clear pattern: building height has a strong influence on heating demand.

Key insights¶

  • The data forms two distinct vertical clusters, corresponding to the two possible building heights in the dataset:

    • 3.5 meters
    • 7.0 meters

  • Buildings with greater height (7.0 m) consistently show higher Heating Load values.
    This is expected, as taller buildings have a larger internal volume and therefore require more energy to maintain comfortable indoor temperatures.

  • The separation between the two clusters is sharp, which aligns with the strong correlation observed earlier between:

    • Overall Height and Heating Load (0.89)
    • Overall Height and Cooling Load (0.90)

  • Within each height group, there is still noticeable variability.
    This suggests that other featuressuch as glazing area, compactness, and roof areaalso contribute to the buildings thermal performance.

This visualization highlights that Overall Height is one of the most influential predictors in the dataset and should be treated as a key variable in the modeling phase.

Cooling Load vs Glazing Area¶

In [11]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="Glazing_Area",
    y="Cooling_Load",
    color="royalblue"
)

plt.title("Glazing Area vs Cooling Load")
plt.show()

Effect of Glazing Area on Cooling Load¶

The scatter plot above shows how different glazing area percentages influence the Cooling Load of the simulated buildings.

Key insights¶

  • The glazing area takes only four discrete values in the dataset: 0.00, 0.10, 0.25, and 0.40.
    This creates four vertical clusters of points in the plot.

  • As the glazing area increases, the median Cooling Load tends to rise.
    This is expected because larger window areas allow more solar heat gains during warm periods, increasing the need for cooling.

  • The spread of Cooling Load values becomes wider at higher glazing percentages.
    This suggests that glazing interacts with other building featuressuch as orientation, compactness, and heightto produce more variability in cooling performance.

  • The relationship is not perfectly linear: the jump from 0.25 to 0.40 glazing area shows a noticeable increase in cooling demand, reinforcing the idea that excessive glazing can significantly reduce energy efficiency.

Overall, this visualization highlights the importance of balancing natural daylight with thermal performance when designing building faades.

Scatterplots coloreados por Glazing Distribution¶

In [12]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))

sns.scatterplot(
    data=df,
    x="Relative_Compactness",
    y="Heating_Load",
    hue="Glazing_Area_Distribution",
    palette="viridis"
)

plt.title("Heating Load vs Relative Compactness (Colored by Glazing Distribution)")
plt.show()

Heating Load vs Relative Compactness (Colored by Glazing Distribution)¶

The scatter plot above shows how Heating Load varies with Relative Compactness, with each point colored according to the buildings Glazing Area Distribution.

Key insights¶

  • The overall trend indicates that higher compactness is associated with higher Heating Load, consistent with earlier observations.
  • Coloring the points by Glazing Area Distribution reveals that this variable does not create clearly separated clusters.
    Instead, the different glazing distributions appear interspersed across the full range of compactness and heating load values.
  • This suggests that glazing distribution has a weaker influence on heating performance compared to other variables such as:
    • Overall Height
    • Roof Area
    • Surface Area
  • However, some subtle patterns can still be observed:
    • Buildings with glazing concentrated on specific facades (e.g., distribution values 3, 4, 5) tend to show slightly higher variability in Heating Load.
    • Uniform glazing distributions (e.g., value 0) appear more tightly grouped.

Overall, this visualization confirms that Relative Compactness and Overall Height are the dominant drivers of Heating Load, while Glazing Distribution plays a secondary role. Still, including it in the model may help capture small but meaningful variations in energy performance.

Cooling Load vs Surface Area (Colored by Glazing Distribution)¶

The scatter plot above illustrates how Cooling Load varies with Surface Area, with each point colored according to the buildings Glazing Area Distribution.

Key insights¶

  • The plot shows a clear upward trend: buildings with larger surface areas tend to require higher cooling loads.
    This aligns with the idea that greater exposed surface increases solar heat gains and thermal exchange with the environment.

  • Coloring the points by Glazing Area Distribution reveals that this variable does not create distinct clusters.
    Instead, all glazing distribution categories appear spread across the full range of surface areas and cooling loads.

  • This suggests that surface area is a much stronger driver of cooling demand than glazing distribution.
    The influence of glazing distribution appears secondary and does not dominate the overall pattern.

  • However, some subtle differences can be observed:

    • Buildings with glazing concentrated on specific facades (distribution values 3, 4, 5) show slightly higher variability in cooling load.
    • More uniform glazing distributions (value 0) appear more tightly grouped.

Overall, this visualization reinforces the idea that Surface Area and Overall Height are among the most influential predictors of cooling performance, while Glazing Distribution contributes smaller, more nuanced effects.

Pairplot para ver clusters¶

sns.pairplot(
    df[[
        "Relative_Compactness",
        "Surface_Area",
        "Overall_Height",
        "Glazing_Area",
        "Heating_Load",
        "Cooling_Load",
        "Glazing_Area_Distribution"
    ]],
    hue="Glazing_Area_Distribution",
    palette="viridis",
    diag_kind="kde"
)
Out[14]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x23dca021510>

Pairplot of Key Features (Colored by Glazing Distribution)¶

The pairplot above provides a comprehensive view of the relationships between the main architectural features and the energy performance variables in the dataset. Each point is colored according to the buildings Glazing Area Distribution, allowing us to observe how this categorical variable interacts with the others.

Key insights¶

  • Strong linear relationships are visible between several variables:

    • Heating Load and Cooling Load show an almost perfect linear correlation, consistent with the correlation matrix.
    • Relative Compactness and Surface Area display a strong inverse relationship, as expected from the geometric constraints of the simulated buildings.
    • Overall Height and Roof Area also show a clear negative relationship.

  • The diagonal plots reveal the distribution shape of each variable:

    • Heating and Cooling Loads exhibit bimodal distributions, confirming the presence of two dominant building configurations.
    • Relative Compactness and Surface Area show narrow, well-defined ranges due to the controlled nature of the simulation.

  • Coloring by Glazing Area Distribution shows that this variable does not create distinct clusters in most feature combinations.
    This reinforces the idea that glazing distribution has a secondary influence compared to variables like height, compactness, and surface area.

  • Some subtle patterns emerge:

    • Buildings with glazing concentrated on specific facades (distribution values 3, 4, 5) show slightly more spread in Heating and Cooling Loads.
    • Uniform glazing distributions (value 0) tend to cluster more tightly.

Overall, the pairplot confirms that Overall Height, Surface Area, and Relative Compactness are the dominant drivers of energy demand, while Glazing Area Distribution contributes smaller, more nuanced effects. This visualization is especially useful for identifying non-linear relationships and guiding the selection of appropriate machine learning models.
